But
the
scripture
saieth:
The
Lorde

vexed
Pharao
and
all
his
house
with

great
plagues,
because
of
Sara
Abra

hams
wife.
Lo
here
the
king
of
Aegypt

is
punished
with
gevous
plagues
for

his
adultery:
and
yet
he
knew
not
that

Sara
was
Abrahams
wife:
how
great

plagues
therfore
are
prepared
for
the

men
that
wittingly
&
willingly
with

out
all
shame
commit
adulterie?
To

Abimelech
king
of
the
Philistines
the

Lord
doth
say:
Loe
thou
shalt
die
be

cause
of
the
woman,
which
thou
hast

taken
away
from
her
husbande.
And

yet
this
king
also
had
taken
away
Sa

ra,
not
knowing
that
shee
was
Abra

hams
wife.
Joseph
beeing
provoked
to

adulterie
by
his
maisters
wife,
doeth

simply
saye:
Howe
shoulde
I
doe
this

great
wickednesse,
and
sinne
against

God?
Everie
worde
doth
beare
some

weight.
For
adulterie
is
an
heynous

sinne.
Whereuppon
in
the
Booke
of

Job
wee
finde
these
wordes
of
Job
him

selfe.
If
mine
heart
have
bin
decei

ved
by
a
woman,
or
if
I
have
layde

waite
at
my
neighbors
doore,
then

let
my
wife
bee
an
other
mansharlot,

and
let
other
men
have
to
do
with
her.

For
this
is
a
wickednesse
and
sinne

that
is
worthie
to
be
judged
to
death.

Yea,
it
is
a
fire
that
utterly
should
con

sumer
and
roote
out
all
mind
increase.

Job
saith,
that
hee
hath
not
onelie
not

committed
adultery,
but
that
hee
hath

not
so
much
at
any
time
as
once
given

the
attempte
to
defile
an
other
mans

wife.
He
confesseth
that
adultery
is
a

sin,
&
so
grievous
an
offence,
taht
it
do

eth
deserve
to
have
ye
adulterers
wife

to
be
defiled
with
adultery.
He
addeth,

that
adultery
is
a
fire
that
utterly
co

sumeth
and
dovoureth
al
thinges,
and

lastly
that
it
is
a
sinne
to
be
judged
&

punished
by
death.

Moreover
Salomon
the
wisest
of
al

men
saith:
May
a
man
take
fire
in
his

bosome
&
his
clothes
not
bee
brent?

Or
can
one
goe
uppon
hot
coales,
and

his
feete
not
bee
burnt:
Even
so
hee

that
goeth
into
his
neighbours
wife,

and
toucheth
her,
cannot
be
unguil

tie.
Men
doe
not
utterly
despise
a

theese,
that
stealeth
to
satisfie
his

soule
when
he
is
hungrie:
But
if
he

may
be
gotten,
he
restoreth
agayne

seven
times
as
much,
or
else
hee
ma

keth
recompence
with
all
the
sub

staunce
of
his
house.
But
who
so
com

mitteth
adulterie
with
a
woman,
hee

lacketh
understanding:
and
hee
that

doth
it
destroieth
his
owne
soule.
He

getteth
himselfe
a
plague
and
disho

nour,
and
his
reproch
shall
never
bee

put
out.
For
the
jealousie
and
wrath

of
the
man
will
not
be
intreated
ney

ther
accepteth
hee
the
person
of
anye

Mediatour,
nor
recieveth
anie
giftes,

howe
great
forever
they
bee.
In
these

words
of
Salomon
many
things
are
to

be
noted.
First
as
it
cannot
otherwise

be,
but
that
fire
must
burn
the
garmet

wherein
it
is
carried:
so
no
man
can

commit
adulterie
without
damage
&

daunger
of
further
punishment.
Se

condarily
comparison
is
made
betwixt

a
theef
&
an
adulterer:
not
that
theft
is

therby
defended,
but
because
theeves,

although
they
bee
infamous,
doe
seeme

yet
to
sinne
a
great
deale
lesse
than
a

dulterers
do.
For
a
theefe
may
make

satisfaction
by
restoring
ye
worth
of
the

thing
that
he
stole,
to
him,
from
whom

hee
stole
it
away:
but
for
adulterie
no

amends
can
be
made.
And
what
is
hee

that
woulde
not
rather
wishe
to
have

Theeves
ransacke
his
Chest,
and
take

awaye
his
substaunce,
than
to
have

his
wife
his
dealing,
defiled
with
ad
ulterie?

Salomo
calleth
the
adul

terer
